Well I will agree to that... It is certainly a bigger struggle to cope with 
a recent car.

My CR-V for some unknown reason requires a dash removal just to replace the 
HVAC pollen filter. I made two cuts in the lower dash brace and I can have 
it out in 5 minutes. Made a bracket to cover the cut and added screws.

With some cars like the one your friend mentioned - there are some 
diminishing returns. That's what I like about my cars - simple enough to 
repair and nice enough to be comfortable...

Buddy of mine got a late model Japanese car for free that only needed a
>"little work"...Electronic problems were such that the car was worthless
>without thousands of dollars in labor to rebuild a cooked electrical system.
>A lot of it was spec'd at just getting access to the wiring, etc. There's
>something to be said for old fashioned nuts and bolts and screws that
>come apart as opposed to the snap fittings and one way barbs that hold
>so much modernity together...;-(

